{[%evp 0,29,16,28,46,51,106,88,88,49,58,55,85,59,90,-2,32,29,28,0,79,33,35,34,
90,57,29,19,14,24,24,1]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {
The readers who already know my previous works for Modern-Chess (hopefully
many of you!) should remember that in 2018 I published a long and detailed
work about the Sicilian Najdorf, which was divided into three databases. It
was one of my first big projects for Modern-Chess, and I was really proud of
the result, which was probably the most updated and complete study of the
Sicilian Najdorf at the time. Well, five years have passed away and we are
back to the initial Najdorf position. Some of you might be wondering why this
database isn't being published as a small update on the 2018 databases. I've
decided to treat these new Najdorf databases as a completely new work by two
main reasons. The first reason is because since 2018 a lot of new ideas have
been found. New variations, move orders, and different approaches that either
escaped my attention or were not trending 5 years ago have appeared in
tournament practice and required careful examination. That means the chapters
are even bigger now than in the first version of the Najdorf databases. Also,
today we have other sources of high-level material to study and improve our
knowledge about the Najdorf. Personally, I like very much Giri's 2020
Chessable Sicilian Najdorf Course. In many chapters, I suggest the same lines
as he and try to go deeper into the positions, although in most of the
variations I still follow my path. The second reason, unfortunately for me, is
that in many lines my analysis didn't survive the test of time (or the test of
modern engines). In some cases, I realized that my analysis was a bit
superficial or incorrect, so I had to do it again with a higher level of
precision. In other cases, I've simply changed my mind about my previous
recommendations and decided to completely change the approach (I've identified
all these positions or lines in my notes). In any case, the result was an
original work and a much better version of my 2018 databases. I hope the
efforts put into making this database can be useful for all Najdorf players :)}
6. Bg5 {This time we opted for a division in only two big databases and
decided to start with the most critical lines. I think all Najdorf player
agrees that although White has a lot of options on move 6, there are three big
main lines that you absolutely need to know how to face. So in the first 4
chapters, we are going to deal with 6.Bg5, is arguably White's most aggressive
option.} ({In Chapter 5 we begin the study of} 6. Be3 {is also a very popular
option. Now we go for the typical Najdorf structure with} e5 7. Nb3 ({Before
entering the English Attack set-ups, we analyze the more positional option} 7.
Nf3 {in Chapter 5.}) 7... Be6 8. f3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Yg2g4,Yh2h4] The famous
English Attack formation. White intends to continue with Qd2, 0-0-0, and to
launch an attack on the kingside by advancing the g an h pawns. Despite
considering 6.Bg5 as the most aggressive, I think the English Attack is
White's objectively best option against the Najdorf. That's because White has
promising chances of attack but the positions are not super forced as in some
lines of 6.Bg5, and because I think here White's position has better
positional foundations in general.} (8. h3 $5 {is a big sideline that gives
many interesting alternative set-ups for White. The practical advantage of
this move is that White doesn't need to remember a lot of theory and still
gets promising chances of attack, especially if Black is caught unprepared. In
Chapter 6 I've analysed all White's plans after this move and how to face them.
}) (8. Qd2 {is a less popular move order. The difference is that by keeping
the pawn on f2 White can consider advancing it two squares at once. So after}
Nbd7 9. O-O-O b5 10. f4 {we have a typical position that is not often seen
nowadays but enjoyed some popularity in the past. White has a simple plan of
attack, but with correct play, Black should be more than fine. The analysis of
this line can be found in Chapter 7.}) 8... h5 $1 {[%csl Yg4,Yh5] I've already
recommended this move in 2018. Time has passed, but this move remains as one
of Black's best options to face the English Attack. The obvious idea is to
make it hard for White to develop the attack on the kingside.} 9. Qd2 Nbd7 {
Regarding the opening plan, White is more or less at a crossroads here.} 10.
Nd5 {is the most played, forcing a transformation on the pawn structure.} ({
Another option is} 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Kb1 {[%cal Gf1d3,Yh2h3,Yg2g4] intending
to continue with moves like Kb1-Bd3-h3 with the goal of insisting on an attack
on the kingside. As usual in Najdorf positions, Black has plenty of resources
to fight for the initiative. Still, the positions can be very complicated and
tense. White's plans are analyzed in detail in Chapter 8.}) 10... Bxd5 11. exd5
g6 $1 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Gf8g7,Yg7g6,Gf8h6] The main point of this move order:
Black can develop the bishop more actively by g7 or h6 sometimes. The
resulting position has an obvious positional unbalance, as White got a
queenside majority and the bishop pair. On the other hand, Black also has a
majority on the kingside and a solid structure. Although the game seems to
take a positional character, it may become very sharp and complex. The
positions are very rich in ideas and resources for both sides, and I've
explained them in Chapter 9.}) (6. Be2 {is the third big line. It's a solid
option that gives an easy development for White and usually leads to a
positional battle.} e5 {Again we reply in the most Najdorf way.} 7. Nb3 (7. Nf3
{gained some popularity a few years ago due to some victories by Carlsen, but
nowadays is considered harmless. In Chapter 10 we see a simple way of solving
Black's opening problems.}) 7... Be7 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gg5f6,
Gc3d5] has the goal of quickly establishing control over the d5-square. It's
the kind of plan that can be unpleasant if you don't know how to play against
it, but once we have studied Chapter 11 it becomes clear that Black is totally
fine.}) 8... O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. Nd5 {This has become White's main option to
fight for an advantage in the last years. The idea is similar to the main line
in the English Attack.} ({One point that makes 6.Be2 attractive for many
players is that White has a lot of different plans available. For players with
an attacking style, for example, it's possible to play} 10. f4 {trying to pose
concrete problems for Black already. However, I don't think such a committal
approach is objectively good for White, so it has lost popularity with time.
Still, it's good to know how to face this kind of aggressive ideas, so I have
analyzed them in Chapter 12.}) ({On the other hand, players with a more
technical style can choose the calm continuation} 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. a4 {aiming
a positional battle. In Chapter 14 I've analysed the "quiet lines", variations
that are objectively harmless but contain many positional traps and subtle
move orders. The study of this chapter surely will improve your strategic
knowledge of Najdorf positions.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Qd3 Bxd5 12. exd5 {[%csl Yd7,
Ge2,Ge3,Yf6] Now we have the same positional imbalance and structure seen in
the main line of the English Attack (Chapter 9), but the game takes a more
positional character.} Rc8 13. c4 Ne8 {In this position} 14. a4 $1 {is
becoming the trend in the last years. The advance of the a-pawn makes sense
with White's plan of expanding on the queenside and adds a few important
subtleties to the position. I had to face this move unprepared in a tournament
game and it proved to be very unpleasant. I was almost convinced that it was
enough to achieve a pleasant advantage for White, but after spending some
hours analysing this position I think I was able to find a satisfactory
solution for Black's problems with the engine's help. You can check my
analysis in Chapter 13.}) ({Finally, I conclude this database with} 6. h3 $5 {
a popular system which also leads to interesting positions. Here I kept my
suggestion from 2018} e6 {which aims to get a complex and double-edged fight.
After} 7. g4 Nfd7 $1 {[%csl Ge1] The character of the upcoming battle is
decided by where White is going to place the king. The positions with 0-0-0
are naturally sharper and more critical. In this case the game leads to a
battle for the initiative and double-edged positions, which are examined in
Chapter 15. In case of 0-0 the game takes a more calm and positional path.
Black is usually able to solve the opening problems very easily in this case,
as can be seen in Chapter 16.}) 6... e6 7. f4 ({In Chapter 1 we examine
possible sidelines for White on move 7.} 7. Qf3 {is the most popular and
probably the most dangerous among them, but there are other less-played
options that are also good to know, including a rare move order employed by
Carlsen in some games.}) 7... h6 8. Bh4 ({In Chapter 2 we are still dealing
with sidelines, this time on move 8. Here I should note that In case of} 8.
Bxf6 {I've changed my recommendation in view of a few recent games in which
White had better prospects.}) 8... Qb6 {[%cal Yh7h6,Gd8b6] Five years later I
still keep my faith on this "Modern Poisoned Pawn" variation. It's true that
white players found some new ideas and the line got some scars, but I still
believe that it is a reliable option for Black.} 9. a3 $1 {The most serious
attempt of advantage for White.} ({Before delving into the two main paths, I
still analysed} 9. Qd3 $5 {as the main line of Chapter 2. It's the kind of
move that might be dangerous to face unprepared, but once you have studied
it's simply harmless.}) ({In Chapter 3 I analyse} 9. Qd2 {which is the
classical approach: White sacrifices the pawn in order to achieve a clear lead
in development. After} Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 {White's plan is to develop the
initiative before Black manages to complete the development. The most played is
} 11. e5 (11. f5 {is also possible, but is considered harmless for Black.})
11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Nfd7 13. Ne4 $1 {White is ready to offer one or two more
pawns in order to get strong pressure in the centre.} Qxa2 14. Rd1 Qd5 15. Qe3
Qxe5 16. Be2 (16. c3 $5 {was an amazing idea used by Caruana to beat Vachier
Lagrave at the 2020-21 Candidates Tournament. Obviously, back then in 2018 I
was not aware that such a move existed, but now I've analyzed it and think
that Black is at least fine in the arising complications.}) 16... Bc5 17. Bg3
Qd5 $1 18. c4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qa5+ 20. Rd2 O-O 21. Bd6 {A critical position from
a theoretical point of view. Black has a strong and important reply here,
which I think more or less solves our opening problems quite well. All of this
is analyzed in detail in Chapter 3, but I think that after having studied this
chapter you will agree with me that 9.Qd2 probably is not enough to achieve an
advantage for White, both from an objective and a practical point of view.})
9... Be7 10. Bf2 Qc7 11. Qf3 {The inclusion of h6/Bh4 has allowed White to get
the most aggressive set-up, with the queen on f3.} Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 Bb7
14. h4 $1 {This has become the main line nowadays.} (14. Bg2 {was the most
played in 2018, but it went out of fashion as Black has a nice plan to solve
the opening problems.}) 14... Nc5 15. Bd3 {This is another important position.
In the 2018 databases I considered 18.h4 as a sideline, so I just briefly
mentioned a recent game (at the time) of mine in which I scored a nice win as
Black. However, that analysis proved to be a bit superficial. So I had to
analyze this position again with new eyes, and the result is that I completely
changed my recommendation. At the first moment, I was really struggling to
find an acceptable path for Black, but even then I still believed in the line.
Finally, I found an interesting idea that renewed my hopes. I managed to
develop it further with the help of a powerful computer and games between
engines and the results made me very happy. I've shared all these discoveries
in Chapter 4.} *

