{[%evp 0,38,31,37,52,47,80,57,57,29,30,27,56,53,53,39,41,18,23,15,15,22,22,-4,
6,8,-2,-11,-14,-20,-18,-21,-21,11,10,-11,16,-5,23,5,1]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3.
d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {Definitely the most ambitious and
aggressive move against the Najdorf. In almost all lines White manages to
develop in a quick and active way, and the positions tend to be sharp and
complicated, rich in tactical ideas for both sides. Attacking players usually
like this variation because White's plan is quite simple: quick and active
development followed by advancing pawns in the centre or on the kingside,
eventual sacrifices, and a mating attack against the enemy king. Obviously,
Black also counts on many resources, and in the arising complications, both
sides fight for the initiative.} e6 (6... Nbd7 $5 {is an interesting and more
flexible alternative.}) 7. Qf3 $5 {Let's start by some sidelines on White's
7th move, from which this is the most popular. The idea is to accelerate
White's development and maneuver the queen to g3, from where it keeps pressure
both in the centre and on the kingside. Although the queen blocks the advance
of the f-pawn, White is able to play either f3 or f4 after an eventual Qg3.
This move has some attacking potential and usually aims to avoid forced and
concrete lines such as the Poisoned Pawn.} (7. Qd2 {is even more popular than
Df3, but I think it doesn't fits well with the bishop on g5. This is a common
set-up for the English Attack (with the bishop on e3).} Be7 ({Previously I had
suggested} 7... h6 {but it seems that after} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nxc6
bxc6 11. f4 {White has better chances, as shown by some recent games.}) 8. f4
$6 ({It's better to play} 8. f3 {or}) (8. O-O-O b5 9. f3 {transposing to the
analysis of 7.f3 seen below.}) 8... b5 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Gf3] The best way of
exploiting White's set-up, as with the queen on f3 Black would have to spend
at least one more move preparing this advance.} 9. e5 {The best reaction
according to the engine, but after} dxe5 10. fxe5 Nfd7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Qf4
Bb7 13. O-O-O O-O $11 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gb8c6,Gf8c8] I like Black's position.
White has no real chances of attack here and should be aware of Black's play
on the queenside. Another point is that the e5-pawn might be a weakness in the
future.}) (7. Qe2 {has the idea of transposing to a dangerous line with 0-0-0
and f4 depriving Black of some options, like the Poisoned Pawn. The drawback
is that we can solve the opening problems by means of a nice tactical resource.
} h6 8. Bh4 (8. Be3 {seems harmless. Black can develop actively with} b5 9. a3
Bb7 10. f3 Nbd7 11. O-O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c3] when the threat of Rxc3 is already
unpleasant.} 12. Qe1 {½-½ Ziatdinov, R (2511)-Browne, W (2516) Koltanowski
Team Match San Francisco 1999 (6) Now} d5 $5 {would give a good game for Black.
For example:} 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Kb1 Qc7 $1 {A precise move,
preventing Nf5-ideas.} 16. c3 Nf6 17. Bd3 Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf6d7,Gd7e5,
Gd7b6] Black has a nice position and excellent prospects in the middlegame.}) (
{In case of} 8. Bxf6 $6 Qxf6 9. O-O-O Nc6 {[%csl Ge2] I like Black's position,
as the queen is much worst placed here compared to the analysis of 7.Qd2.})
8... Be7 9. O-O-O (9. f4 $6 {falls for the same idea:} Nxe4 $1 10. Bxe7 Nxc3
11. Qc4 {when after} Kxe7 12. Qxc3 {[%csl Ge7] the black king in the centre
seemingly offers enough compensation for White. However, after the simple
continuation} Re8 13. O-O-O Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g8] White still needs to prove the
compensation. In one game he tried to do that by means of a quick assault on
the kingside with} 14. Nf3 d5 15. g4 Nc6 16. g5 {but this desperate attempt
can be refuted by active play:} Qd6 $1 17. Qe3 {1-0 Selivanov, I (2160)
-Mischuk, D (2374) Moscow op-A 13th 2017 (7) Black has more than one way of
consolidating his advantage here. I like an aggressive idea suggested by the
engine:} hxg5 18. Nxg5 e5 19. Bg2 Nb4 20. a3 Nxc2 $3 21. Kxc2 Bf5+ $40 {
[%csl Rc2][%cal Ye5f4,Yd5d4,Ga8c8] with a dangerous attack.}) (9. Bg3 $2 {
is the only way of avoiding the tactical resource on e4, but doesn't make too
much sense with White's previous play. After} e5 $1 {Black is already playing
for an advantage. For example:} 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Nbd7 12. f4 Rc8 13. Qd2
O-O 14. Bd3 Qb6 15. O-O-O exf4 16. Bxf4 d5 $19 {[%cal Ge7b4,Yd5d4,Gf6d5] ;0-1
Berchtenbreiter, M (2488)-Perez Ponsa, F (2559) PRO League Stage Chess.com INT
rapid 2020 (1) and Black develops a strong attack on the queenside.}) 9... Nxe4
$1 {The start of a forced sequence which leads to an unbalanced endgame.} 10.
Nxe4 ({Now} 10. Bxe7 Nxc3 11. Qc4 $2 {is bad due to} Nxa2+ $1) 10... Bxh4 11.
Nxe6 $1 {White needs to play concretely in order to justify the lost pawn.} (
11. Nf5 $2 {is an inferior version of the same idea:} exf5 12. Nxd6+ Kf8 13.
Nxf7 Bg5+ $1 14. f4 $5 Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 Kxf7 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Qf3 {½-½
Zambrana, O (2472)-Salih, A (2315) Olympiad-41 Tromsoe 2014 (11.1) Here it's
possible to improve Black's play by means of} Be5 18. Bc4+ Kg6 $1 19. g4 Nc6
20. Bd3 Kh7 $1 {as after} 21. Bxf5+ Bxf5 22. Qxf5+ g6 $19 {Black has no
problems coordinating his pieces, which soon will be stronger than White's
queen.}) 11... Bxe6 12. Nxd6+ Kf8 13. Nxf7 {[%csl Rd8,Rh8] White wins the
queen with this resource, but Black gets enough material in return.} Bg5+ $1 {
It's important to remember this check.} (13... Bxf7 $2 {is imprecise as after}
14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Qf3 $36 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf1c4] ;½-½ Solodovnichenko, Y 
(2587)-Fier, A (2624) FRA-chT Top 12 Drancy 2016 (3.4) White has some
initiative.}) 14. Kb1 (14. f4 $5 {has the goal of attracting the bishop to a
more exposed square.} Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 Kxf7 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Qf3 {[%csl Rb7,Rf4]
This is the point of White's idea, but Black still has the nice reply} Kg8 $1 {
avoiding both threats and keeping the material thanks to back rank motifs.} 18.
Bd3 Be5 19. Qe4 {1-0 Massironi, M (2223)-Cirkvencic, F (2012) Nova Gorica op
24th 2019 (7) This position has occurred in one game. Despite having few
pieces to attack, White managed to win. I imagine that Black didn't play} Nc6 {
in view of} 20. Rf1 {[%cal Ge4h7] but the difference is that with the knight
on c6 (instead of d7, like in the game) he would have} Rxd3 $1 21. cxd3 Re8 $17
{[%cal Ge6f7,Ge5f6,Ge8e7] when White's attack was completely neutralized and
Black can keep coordinating his pieces, with advantage.}) 14... Kxf7 15. Rxd8 (
15. Qh5+ {leads to a curious draw:} g6 16. Rxd8 gxh5 $1 17. Rxh8 Kg7 {and the
rook is trapped on the eighth rank.} 18. Re8 Kf7 19. Rh8 Kg7 $11) 15... Rxd8 {
The biggest question here is whether Black is able to complete the development
and coordinate the pieces first or if White manages to pose enough practical
problems to disturb this plan. In practice all results are possible, but the
analysis shows that Black has decent chances.} 16. Qf3+ (16. h4 $5 $146 {
is an interesting novelty that I had analyzed in 2018 and remains unplayed.}
Be7 17. g4 {Advancing the kingside pawns is a natural way of playing for the
initiative. Here I like} Bd5 18. Rh3 Nc6 19. g5 Rd6 $1 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd6h6]
when Black keeps bringing the pieces to reinforce the king's position. The
position seems complex, but dynamically balanced.}) 16... Bf6 17. Bd3 (17.
Qxb7+ $2 Nd7 {[%cal Ga8b8] only helps Black.}) 17... Nc6 18. Re1 Bd5 {While
Black keeps mobilizing his forces, White is unable to create dangerous threats
with the queen alone.} 19. Qg4 $2 {This is already a mistake.} (19. Qh5+ $2 Kf8
$17 {[%cal Gd5f7] is also better for Black.}) ({The right continuation was} 19.
Be4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Rd7 21. a3 $11 {when White can hardly think about more than
a draw, but his position is at least safe.}) 19... Kf8 $1 {Anticipating any
check and vacating f7 for the bishop.} 20. a3 {½-½ Shabalov, A (2606)-Baklan,
V (2655) FIDE World Cup Khanty-Mansiysk 2009 (1.5) Here Black could have
exploited his better coordination by means of} Ne5 {with a big advantage. For
example:} 21. Qb4+ Kg8 22. Be4 Bf7 $1 $19 {[%cal Ge5c4,Ya6a5,Ga8b8,Yb7b5] when
it's a matter of time until Black launches a decisive attack on the queenside.}
) (7. Qd3 {is the last queen move to consider. The queen is not obstructing
the f-pawn nor the light-squared bishop here, but it has the drawback of
blocking the d-file and being a bit exposed on d3.} b5 {Again it's easier to
develop the queenside actively without the enemy queen on f3. The most played
now is} 8. O-O-O (8. a3 {prevents b5-b4, but it gives one more tempo for
Black's development.} Nbd7 9. f4 $2 {In order to find a concrete sense for his
