1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Qd2
{Before delving into the universe of the classic English Attack positions,
let's examine a plan that is not so popular nowadays, but certainly has some
venom. In this move order, White goes for 0-0-0 immediately and keeps the
f-pawn on its initial square, aiming to play f4-f5.} Nbd7 9. O-O-O (9. h3 b5
10. O-O-O Be7 {transposes to one line seen in the previous chapter.}) 9... b5 {
[%csl Gf8] Since White still has the option of advancing the f-pawn only one
square, I think this move order is the most precise, keeping the bishop on f8.}
10. f4 {[%cal Yf2f4,Yf4f5] This move enjoyed some popularity in the past as
White's plan is quite simple: advancing f2-f4-f5, then continuing with g2-g4,
sacrificing a pawn to open the g-file. The arising positions offer nice
practical chances of attack, with the advantage that White doesn't have to
enter heavy theoretical discussions as after 10.f3.} (10. f3 h5 $1 {transposes
to the main line of the English Attack.}) 10... Be7 11. f5 ({It's also
possible to start with} 11. Kb1 {and after} O-O {go for} 12. f5 Bc4 13. g4 $5 {
but as strange as it may look, the tempo spent with the king makes White's
attack less promising.} (13. Rg1 {has scored well in the database, but seems a
bit slow. Black can take advantage of it by means of} Bxf1 14. Rdxf1 b4 15. Nd5
a5 {and the pawns keep advancing on the queenside. This position has occurred
in a recent game. White played} 16. g4 {but Black found an instructive
solution against the advance of the kingside pawns.} a4 17. Nc1 Nxd5 18. exd5
Qa5 19. g5 {Now he found} Bd8 $1 {[%csl Gd8] an excellent prophylactic measure
against f5-f6, making it very hard for White to get open files for her rooks
on the kingside. The game went} 20. f6 g6 $1 21. Rg4 Bb6 $1 {[%csl Gb6,Ge3]
[%cal Gf8c8] ;0-1 Mammadzada, G (2425)-Gopal, G (2594) Riga Tech op-A 2019 (3)
Another instructive idea, exchanging the bad bishop and getting ready to
activate the f8-rook. The position is dynamically balanced, but Black
eventually won after a tense fight.}) (13. h3 {is also slow. Now Black gets a
good game with} a5 $1 14. g4 Bxf1 15. Rhxf1 {1-0 Bruzon Batista, L (2569)-Vera
Gonzalez Quevedo, R (2537) Capablanca Memorial Elite 37th Havana 2002 (9) Here
a good continuation would be} a4 16. Nc1 b4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 $6 ({More
precise is} 18. exd5 Qa5 19. g5 {and now the correct way to face White's plan
is} f6 20. h4 Rfc8 {with a tense but balanced position. An important point is
that if} 21. g6 {Black has} h6 $1 {since the sacrifice} 22. Bxh6 $2 gxh6 23.
Qxh6 {is refuted by} Nf8 $1 $17 {and White is unable to develop the attack.})
18... h6 $1 {Black has prevented all the breakthroughs on the kingside and can
develop his play on the other side without problems, for instance:} 19. Qd3 $2
Qc7 $17 {[%cal Gf8c8,Ya4a3] and Black's attack is clearly more dangerous.})
13... Nxg4 {We can and should accept the pawn without fearing the
complications. As we'll see, Black has more than enough resources to defend
his position.} 14. Rg1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bxb3 $1 {This move, found by Karjakin, in
practice is a refutation for the 11.Rb1 move order. At the first sight, it
might look like a strange decision to leave White with the light-squared
bishop in this structure. However, if we think in terms of attacking prospects
the knight would be much more annoying, as it could join the actions on the
kingside more easily.} 16. Qh6 $2 {Insisting on an attack that doesn't exist.}
({In one game White played} 16. cxb3 $5 {which seems the best option
objectively speaking, forgetting about the attack and expecting to get
positional compensation for the pawn. The game went} Kh8 17. Be2 {0-1 Alboredo,
J (2175)-Salinas Herrera, P (2498) American Continental 15th Sao Paulo 2019 (4)
Now} Nf6 {seems natural, and if} 18. Rg3 {as in the game, Black has} b4 19. Nd5
Nxd5 20. Rxd5 h6 $11 {[%cal Ya6a5,Ge7g5] with a balanced position, but Black
remains a pawn up and has no problems.}) 16... Bxc2+ $1 {The bishop was lost
anyway, so Black uses it to grab a second pawn and expose White's king.} 17.
Kxc2 Bf6 18. Rxd6 (18. Rd3 {doesn't improve White's chances, as after} Kh8 19.
Qh5 {we can set a solid defense by means of} h6 $1 20. Rh3 Kh7 {when despite
having all heavy pieces on the kingside, White can't break through the defense.
The following variation is very instructive:} 21. Nd5 {Very logical, trying to
maneuver the knight to the kingside. The drawback is that the king feels a bit
alone on the queenside now.} Rc8+ 22. Kb1 Nb6 $1 23. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3g4] The
knight is almost making it to the kingside, but we still have the strong
resource} Qc7 24. Bd3 Qc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5g1,Yd6d5] and suddenly it's Black who
takes the initiative. For example:} 25. Rd1 Kg8 $1 {[%cal Gf6g5]} 26. Rg3 Rfd8
$1 27. Qxh6 Kf8 $1 $17 {[%cal Gf8e7,Yd6d5] The king finds a safe place on e7
and Black soon breaks in the centre with d6-d5, with a very active position.})
18... Kh8 19. Qd2 ({Another game went} 19. Qh5 {but Black still had a big
advantage after} Qe7 20. Qd1 Rfd8 21. a3 Nb6 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Qc1 b4 $19 {
0-1 Salgado Lopez, I (2554)-Zakhartsov, V (2529) Cappelle op 25th
Cappelle-la-Grande 2009 (9) with a winning attack.}) 19... Ra7 {[%csl Rc2]
Black's position is clearly better. The pressure on the d-file is not a
problem and White's king is more vulnerable. On the top, Black remains a pawn
