14,55,34,51,29,29,3,43,10,38,6,21,-4]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 {Finally, the classic move order of
the English Attack. White's most common plan is to continue with Qd2 and 0-0-0,
followed by the advance of the g an h-pawns and an offensive on the kingside.
Black has tried many different plans against the English Attack, always
leading to complex positions and a tense fight. My recommendation is the
attempt of trying to prevent White's main plan with} h5 $1 {[%csl Yg4,Gh5] an
interesting variation that has become one of Black's main weapons in the last
years. Although usually it is not advisable to move pawns on the side where
you are going to be attacked, in this case, there is a clear goal: to avoid -
or at least to make it harder - White's g4-advance. Now White has a choice
between insisting on a direct attack or taking a positional approach. Let's
start with the first option.} 9. Qd2 (9. Be2 {is a more calm alternative. The
main idea is to develop like in the positions of 6.Be2 and try to take some
advantage from the inclusion of h7-h5 in Black's position, but practice has
proven that this is not enough to bring an advantage for White.} Nbd7 {As
usual, while White can still consider Nd5 we should keep the bishop on f8.} 10.
a4 (10. O-O {is the most played, but with the queenside developed Black can
play} b5 {with a nice position.} 11. Qd2 Be7 12. Rfd1 Nb6 13. Bf1 Qc7 14. Qf2 {
½-½ Ivanchuk, V (2741)-Dominguez Perez, L (2655) Capablanca Memorial Elite
Havana 2006 (3) Black already has an easier game and could have obtained an
advantage by means of} Nc4 15. Bxc4 bxc4 16. Nc1 O-O 17. N1e2 Qb7 $1 {[%cal
Yd6d5] followed by the freeing d5-advance. A nice detail is that} 18. Bg5 $2 {
is bad due to} Ng4 $1 19. fxg4 Bxg5 20. gxh5 Qxb2 $17 {[%csl Ge6,Gg5] and
Black has an excellent position.}) (10. f4 $5 {as we'll see in the following
variations, this advance can be considered in many moments. The difference is
that in this move order, it can be combined with 0-0, with a more controlled
position than in case of opposite castles.} Qc7 11. h3 (11. f5 {was played
once, but seems harmless.} Bc4 12. Nd2 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 {½-½ Borriss, M (2445)
-Bischoff, K (2564) Bundesliga 0304 Germany 2003 (9.4) The game was a quick
draw, but a possible continuation would be} b5 14. a3 Be7 15. O-O O-O {when}
16. h3 {[%cal Yg2g4] with the idea of expanding on the kingside is still
White's main idea. Black shouldn't fear this plan though, as after} Rfc8 17. g4
{we have} d5 $1 {a typical reaction to the g4-advance. After} 18. exd5 b4 19.
axb4 Bxb4 $132 {Black has nice counterplay.}) 11... Be7 12. O-O {1-0
Cheparinov, I (2686)-Aczel, G (2474) SLO-chT 32nd Ljubljana 2022 (6.5) White's
move order has a clever point: the opening started with the English Attack,
but now it has transposed to a position which resembles the 6.Be2 variation
with a pawn on h5. The question is: how should Black continue the development?
He didn't find a good answer for this problem in the game. Let's see how
Black's play might be improved, starting with} b5 13. a3 {and now} O-O $5 {
is an interesting sacrifice suggested by the engine.} 14. Bxh5 (14. f5 Bc4 {
seems ok for Black, for example:} 15. Bxc4 Qxc4 16. Qf3 a5 $132 {[%cal Yb5b4]})
14... Nxh5 15. Qxh5 a5 $1 {[%cal Yb5b4,Gf8c8,Gd7f6] The bishop pair and active
piece play provide enough compensation for the pawn. For example:} 16. Qd1 Rfc8
17. Rf2 Qb7 18. Qf3 Nf6 $44 {[%cal Yb5b4] and the constant threat of b4 always
bothers White.}) 10... Rc8 11. O-O (11. a5 Be7 12. O-O O-O {is the same.})
11... Be7 12. Qd2 O-O {The position is the same as seen in some lines of 6.Be2
with the pawn on h5. Still, the games show that White is unable to take any
advantage of either the pawn or the g5-square.} 13. a5 Qc7 14. Rfd1 (14. Rfc1 {
[%cal Gc3d5] is a common way of preparing the knight's jump to d5. Black can
continue developing with} Rfe8 {and keep waiting. In one game White played} 15.
Nd5 {immediately, but after} Bxd5 16. exd5 Nc5 $5 17. Nxc5 dxc5 18. c4 Bd6 {
[%cal Ye5e4] Black has nice chances of counterplay. The game went} 19. b4 $6
Qe7 20. b5 $2 {but} e4 $1 {[%cal Gd6h2,Ge8e1] seems already dangerous. White
