Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 h5 $1 {As we've seen in the last chapter,
this move makes the typical English Attack ideas harder. White's most
promising plan then is to force a transformation in the pawn structure by
means of Nd5 at some point. After the exchange on d5 the new structure is not
exactly new for us (see Chapter 13), but the presence of the pawn on h5 and
some differences on both sides set-ups make the position simply different,
with its own features and possibilities. In this new structure, White has the
bishop pair and a slight space advantage. Despite White's main plan being to
exploit the majority on the queenside, we should not forget that the h5-pawn
also makes it possible to consider some ideas on the kingside. From Black's
perspective, we should try to keep the queenside as safe and closed as
possible, while at the same time preparing our counterplay on the kingside by
advancing the e and f pawns, and sometimes with h4-h3. Here the battle usually
takes a positional character, with both sides trying to prevent the opponent's
plan. At the same time, we have the typical tension of Sicilian positions, as
the game suddenly can become open and sharp. As you can imagine by this long
introduction, this line leads to positions complex and rich in ideas for both
