20... Bg5 $1 {Black improves his pieces and at the same time makes White's
plan of maneuvering the knight to d5 harder.} 21. Nb3 ({After} 21. Nf3 Be7 {
[%csl Gf3] the knight is still far from its goal.}) 21... Qc6 $5 {[%csl Ye4]} (
21... Nd7 {was also playable.}) 22. Na5 (22. Nxc5 dxc5 23. Rd5 {is harmless in
view of} c4 $1 {when} 24. Rxe5 Rd2 $1 {seems even more dangerous for White,
for instance:} 25. Rxg5 $2 Qf6 $19 {[%csl Rf2,Rg5]}) (22. f3 $2 d5 $1 $17 {
likely was Giri's idea, with advantage for Black.}) 22... Qc7 23. Nb3 Qc6 24.
Rd5 Nd7 $1 $11 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gd7b6,Yd6d5] ;½-½ Carlsen, M (2834)-Giri, A 
(2784) Qatar Masters op Doha 2015 (7) Black is ok, and in the game he even had
some initiative. I should mention that Giri's games in the Najdorf are always
instructive, especially in positional variations in which White tries to
exploit the d5-square. The Dutch GM knows how to solve Black's strategic
problems and skillfully takes advantage of any small imprecision by his
opponents. Finally, a useful reminder in such positions is that the knight is
a very important piece to keep d5 under control and also to help on Black's
counterplay. Whenever that is possible, keeping it in the game is a good idea.}
