14. fxe5 Nxe5 $15 {[%csl Rg1] Despite the simplifications, the exposed nature
of White's king makes Black's position a bit more comfortable.}) 10... exf4 $1
{This reaction is almost always playable, but here it is even more justified.}
11. Bxf4 {[%csl Yd5,Ye5][%cal Gc1e3,Ge3f4] A nice point is that White has
spent two tempos with the bishop, going to e3 and then f4. The arising
structure is very important to understand, as it can appear in many variations
of the Najdorf. White has the open f-file and prospects of bringing more
pieces to the kingside, with Nd4-f5, for example. On the other hand, Black can
exploit the diagonal a7-g1 to create threats against the enemy king and the
open e-file to attack the e4-pawn. Just like White has d5, Black has a strong
point for the knight on e5 (or the bishop, although this is less common). The
d5-square still matters a bit, but since the position is more open the battle
can become sharper.} (11. Rxf4 {is the alternative to not spend another tempo
with the bishop. White can exploit the position of the rook to play a quick
Nd5, but this doesn't seems enough to get an advantage.} Nc6 12. Nd5 $5 {
The only way to make use of the rook on f4.} (12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nd7 $1 $15
{[%cal Ge7g5,Gd7e5] is more than fine for Black.}) ({In case of slow play by
White, Black can continue developing without problems. The following game is
an instructive example:} 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Rd1 Ne5 {White struggles to create
new ideas, as Black's position is very solid.} 14. Nd4 b5 15. a3 g6 $5 {
[%csl Gf5] Since the exchange on e6 is not a real threat, since it just
improves Black's structure, it is good to prevent Nf5.} 16. Rdf1 $2 Bc4 $1 {
Another strong move, gaining control over c4. Now White erred with} 17. Kh1 $2
{and after} d5 $1 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 {0-1 Kantane, A (2259)-Xiong,
J (2667) PRO League Stage Chess.com INT rapid 2017 (5) Black already has a
little annoying pressure.}) 12... Bxd5 $1 13. exd5 Ne5 {An instructive
transformation in the structure: White has exchanged the outpost on d5 and the
pressure on d6 for a majority on the queenside. The next plan is to prepare
the advance of the pawns, with the goal of either creating a passed pawn or
cramping Black's position. From my practical experience, Black should be fine
if we keep the Ne5 well-supported and a firm control over the c5-square, which
is White's main point for a breakthrough. A typical regrouping idea is
Nfd7-Bg5, controlling c5 and trying to exchange the bishops, which is a nice
positional operation for Black, leaving White with a bad bishop and many
problems on the dark squares.} 14. Rb4 $5 {Trying to find a useful role for
the rook.} ({The following game is an instructive example of how Black can
improve his position quickly in case of careless play:} 14. c4 Nfd7 $1 {
[%cal Gd7c5,Ge7g5]} 15. Rf1 Rc8 16. Rc1 Bg5 $1 {After this exchange I already
like Black's position.} 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Nd4 g6 19. Rc3 Nc5 20. Rg3 Qd8 $11 {
[%csl Ge5] ;0-1 Kula, R (2341)-Olszewski, M (2526) Police Gniota Memorial 27th
2012 (4) The position is still balanced, but in practice I like Black's
chances. It's always harder to suggest a plan for White, as his pieces can
hardly be improved. Further ideas would require pawn advances and concrete
actions, which might compromise his position. On the other hand, Black always
has the Ne5 keeping everything under control and enjoying more freedom of
maneuvering. For example, Black can prepare breakthroughs and pawn advances on
both flanks or to develop active play by the e-file, only to mention a few
ideas.}) 14... Qc7 15. a4 {Aiming to restrict Black's queenside. A nice way of
regrouping the pieces now is} Nfd7 16. a5 Bf6 {when Black is well coordinated
and keeps many important points under control.} 17. Qd2 Rfe8 18. Rf1 Ng6 $5 {
The start of a creative plan.} 19. c3 Re5 $1 {[%cal Ga8e8]} 20. Rc4 Qd8 21. Bg4
Qe8 $1 {Black is already playing for the advantage. The game went} 22. Bf2 (22.
Rc7 $2 {has a tactical refutation:} Rxe3 $1 23. Bxd7 Qd8 24. Rxb7 Re7 25. Bc6
Rxb7 26. Bxb7 Rb8 $19 {[%csl Rb3,Rb7] and Black wins a piece.}) {Here Black
found another strong regroupment:} 22... Bg5 $1 23. Qd1 Nf6 $1 24. Bf3 Be3 $1
$15 {0-1 Li, R (2446)-Troff, K (2517) Saint Louis SPICE Cup op 9th 2015 (3)
Black skillfully managed to force the exchange of the dark-squared bishop.
This is a big positional achievement, as now it's easier to exploit the
weaknesses on White's camp. Black showed excellent technique from this point
