This is nowadays one of the main moves against the Najdorf and is very popular
in all levels. In theoretical databases, this line receives the name of Adams
Attack, not because of the famous English GM Michael Adams, but from another
Adams, who played it for the first time in 1948! Many years later, after some
victories by Fischer put this variation more seriously in tournament practice.
White's goal couldn't be clearer: to continue with g4, like in the Keres
Attack. I've decided to divide the study of this line in two chapters,
according to the side White castles go. Let's start by the most critical lines,
with 0-0-0.} e6 $5 {This is another case where I suggest the Scheveningen
structure instead of 6...e5. Of course, this allows White to continue the
opening plan and leads to complex positions, but I don't think Black's chances
are worse.} (6... e5 {is the most played. Depending to where White retreats
the knight, Black can continue with h5 in order to restrict the kingside play.
