bishops gives a small but pleasant advantage for Black.}) (11. Qe2 Nxd4 12.
Bxd4 b5 $1 {transposes to 9.Be3 Nc6 10.Qe2.}) (11. a4 {seems harmless.} Nde5
12. b3 Ng6 13. Qd2 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bg5 $1 {Taking the chance of developing play
on the dark squares.} 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 e5 $5 {[%csl Gf4,Yg2] The
positional threat of Nf4 more or less forces White to respond with} 17. Ne2 {
[%cal Yf2f4] followed by f2-f4.} Be6 18. f4 exf4 19. Nxf4 {½-½ Vuilleumier,
A (2356)-Yu, Y (2747) Gibraltar Masters 14th Caleta 2016 (1) Now} Nxf4 {
would keep a slight advantage for Black, for example:} 20. Rxf4 Rc8 21. Rf2 Rc5
22. Rd1 Qc7 23. Qd3 Rd8 $15 {Despite keeping some pressure on d6 by now,
White's weaknesses can prove more difficult to keep under control in the long
run.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 ({In case of} 12. Bxd4 {we can play} b5 $1 {
immediately, as} 13. e5 $2 {is a mistake.} (13. a3 Bb7 {is safer, but in this
case Black has a comfortable game.}) 13... dxe5 $1 {The analysis shows that
this is much better than closing the centre with d6-d5:} 14. fxe5 (14. Bxe5 Ra7
15. Bd4 Nb6 $17 {[%cal Ga7d7] is simply better for Black.}) ({Accepting the
exchange is even worse:} 14. Bxa8 $2 exd4 15. Ne2 Nb6 16. Bf3 Bc5 17. Qd3 Nc4
$19 {[%cal Gc4e3,Gc4b2,Ye6e5] and Black's position is already winning.}) 14...
Rb8 15. Ne4 Bb7 16. Qd3 Qc7 $17 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8c8,Gd7c5,Gf8d8] ;½-½
Polzin, R (2416)-Raykhman, A (2414) Bundesliga 1516 Germany 2015 (4.6) White
has a serious weakness on e5 and many exposed squares in his camp, with a very
difficult position. The simplest path now would be to prepare the exchange of
all minor pieces with Nc5, after which White would be in trouble not only with
the e5-pawn but also with an weak king.}) 12... e5 $1 {The most direct to
solve Black's opening problems.} (12... b5 $5 {is a more combative option,
also playable.} 13. a4 $5 ({Another game went} 13. Qd2 Bb7 14. g5 Rc8 15. Ne2
Rc4 16. b3 Rc7 17. Ng3 Qa8 18. f5 Rfc8 $132 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Yd6d5] ;½-½
Caruana, F (2675)-Ivanchuk, V (2749) Corus Wijk aan Zee 2010 (1) with a
double-edged game. Besides the pressure on c2, Black can consider d6-d5 with
active play in the centre.}) 13... bxa4 14. Qxa4 Rb8 $15 {½-½ Nepomniachtchi,
I (2695)-Dominguez Perez, L (2713) Capablanca Memorial Elite 45th Havana 2010 
(9) Black has a potential weakness on a6, but the pressure on the c and
b-files makes his position even easier to play.}) 13. Qd2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Ne5 {
[%csl Yd6,Ge5,Yg2] A typical structure in the Najdorf: Black has an isolated
pawn on d6, but the knight gets a nice outpost on e5. An important point is
that the bishop on g2 lacks good prospects, and White's opening strategy has
led to the creation of weaknesses on the kingside. I already like Black's
position.} 15. Nd5 Be6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Rad1 Rfd8 {This position has
occurred three times in tournament practice. Despite it is objectively
balanced, Black won all games. In one of them, Giri showed how to organize
Black's play in an instructive way:} 18. Rf2 b5 19. b3 Qc7 20. Qe3 Rd7 21. Rfd2
h6 22. Qf2 f6 $1 $15 {[%csl Ge5] ;0-1 Brandenburg, D (2535)-Giri, A (2687)
NED-ch Boxtel 2011 (6) Black reinforces the knight and establishes a strong
control over e5 and the dark squares on the kingside. The way as the structure
was fixed on both flanks makes the Bg2 very passive. Black has many
interesting plans at his disposal, such as increasing the pressure on the
c-file, opening the queenside by means of a5-a4 or to weaken the enemy king
with h6-h5 at some point. As White needs to be constantly aware of these ideas,
his position tends to be a bit more unpleasant. Although the position should
be balanced with correct play, in practice things proved to be more difficult,
and Black managed to win.} *

