{Since Najdorf is a highly complex opening, nobody can learn everything.
Therefore, in the next couple of lines, I present the most important must-know
lines in every direction. By studying these chapters, you will be more than
ready to start playing the Najdorf!}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Bg5 - You Must Know"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B94"]
[Annotator "GM Renato Quintiliano"]
[PlyCount "42"]

{[%evp 0,17,25,24,51,32,62,48,42,26,27,24,55,62,59,19,18,19,12,0]} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {From my experience, I can say
this is White's most aggressive option and the most dangerous weapon against
the Najdorf. White has a clear attacking plan with f4-Qf3-0-0-0, and Black
needs to be well prepared for the ensuing complications.} e6 7. f4 (7. Qf3 {
is a popular sideline for White. Here I like} h6 $5 {forcing a definition by
the bishop. Now I think} 8. Be3 $5 {is the most promising retreat.} (8. Bh4 {
is the most played, but the bishop might be misplaced on h4 sometimes.} Nbd7 9.
O-O-O Qc7 {[%cal Yb7b5,Gc8b7] Black prepares to develop active play on the
queenside.} 10. Be2 $6 {A tricky but objectively dubious idea.} (10. Bd3 {
seems more natural.} Be7 11. Kb1 Rb8 $1 (11... b5 $2 {allows a similar
resource seen after 10.Be2:} 12. e5 Bb7 13. Nxe6 $3 fxe6 14. exf6 Bxf3 15. Bg6+
$1 Kf8 16. fxe7+ Kg8 17. gxf3 $18 {[%cal Ye7e8] White still grabs one more
rook for the queen.}) 12. Qh3 b5 13. f4 $1 b4 $1 {The position becomes sharp
now.} 14. Na4 $1 (14. Nce2 {is inferior as after something like} Nc5 15. Ng3 $2
{Black has} e5 16. Ndf5 g6 $19 {winning a piece.}) 14... Nc5 15. e5 $1 {
White keeps increasing the tension in order to complicate the game. After} Nxa4
16. exf6 gxf6 $13 {Azarov,S (2588)-Idani,P (2635) Sharjah Masters 5th 2022 (5)
0-1 the position is double-edged.}) 10... Be7 ({Here it's important to
remember that} 10... b5 $2 {falls for the trick} 11. e5 $1 Bb7 12. Nxe6 $3 fxe6
13. Qh5+ $1 {The point on developing the bishop by e2. Black has nothing
better than} Kd8 {but after} 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Qg6 $18 {[%csl Rd8] ;Schutt,R 
(2147)-Quintiliano Pinto, R (2340) Foz do Iguacu op 1st 2013 (4) 1/2-1/2 White
clearly has a winning position.}) 11. Rhe1 Rb8 $5 {[%cal Yb7b5] Black is ready
for b5. Although White's pieces are all centralized, it's hard to find a
constructive plan. Meanwhile, Black's play on the queenside is supernatural
and dangerous. In one game White played} 12. Qh3 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Yf2f4,Yf4f5]
a multi-purpose move: The queen cleans the path to the f-pawn, keeps an eye on
possible sacrifices on e6, and prevents g7-g5 by Black. Still, after} b5 13. f4
b4 {It's White who needs to make a difficult decision. He played} 14. Nb1 $2 {
[%cal Gb1d2] ;Kortschnoj,V (2642)-Sadvakasov,D (2523) Astana m 2003 (7) 1/2-1/
2 intending to bring the knight back to the game by d2.} (14. Na4 {[%csl Ra4]
was better, but it's obviously unpleasant to play with such a misplaced knight
on a4. Now Black has the strong reply} g6 $1 {[%cal Ye6e5] with the dangerous
threat of e5, when White is in trouble.}) 14... Nc5 {seems the simplest way to
achieve a clear advantage for Black now. For example:} 15. e5 (15. Nd2 $2 {
is bad in view of} e5 16. Nf5 g6 $19 {winning a piece.}) 15... dxe5 16. fxe5
Nd5 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Nd2 Bb7 19. Nc4 O-O $17 {[%csl Re5,Gg8] Black has active
play, the safer king, and a superior structure.}) (8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6
$11 {[%csl Gc8,Yd6,Ye6,Ye8,Yf6,Yf7,Gf8] The endgame is balanced, but in
practice I even prefer Black's chances. We have the bishop pair and a strong
pawn centre which can be exploited in the long run. Also, an important point
is that Black's king feels totally safe in the centre now that the queens have
been exchanged.}) 8... e5 $5 {Now we transpose to the typical Najdorf
structure.} (8... Be7 $2 9. O-O-O O-O $2 {is too careless. After} 10. g4 $1 $18
{[%cal Yh2h4,Yg4g5] White has a crushing attack. This is the main point of
retreating the bishop to e3.}) 9. Nb3 Be7 $1 {The right move order, keeping
the bishop on c8. The point will be clear in the next moves.} (9... Be6 $6 10.
Nd5 $1 Nbd7 11. c4 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1] gives a pleasant advantage for
White.}) (9... b5 {was my previous recommendation, but after} 10. a4 $1 b4 11.
Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd7 13. Nd2 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gf1d3,Yg2g4] White has
strong play on the light squares.}) 10. h3 {[%cal Yg2g4,Ge1c1] White prepares
both 0-0-0 and g4 with this move.} b5 $1 {Black is better prepared for this
advance now.} 11. O-O-O ({The difference is that now if} 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5
$1 13. exd5 O-O {[%cal Yf7f5,Ya6a5,Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gc8b7] the advantage of keeping
the bishop on c8 is that Black doesn't have to spend one tempo retreating it
to c8 again. Instead, we can use that saved tempo to improve our structure on
both flanks and develop more actively.}) 11... b4 $1 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 a5
$1 $132 {[%cal Ya5a4] Again, the tempo saved by leaving the bishop on c8
allows Black to develop the counterplay on the queenside more quickly. The
position is double-edged as usual, but Black's chances are not inferior.}) (7.
Qe2 {is a tricky move order. White intends to continue with 0-0-0 and f4,
transposing to a popular version without allowing the Poisoned Pawn. However,
Black has a nice resource to prevent this plan.} h6 8. Bh4 Be7 9. O-O-O (9. f4
$6 {falls for the same idea:} Nxe4 $1 10. Bxe7 Nxc3 {The difference is that
here White can play} 11. Qc4 Kxe7 12. Qxc3 {[%csl Ge7] when Black's king in
the centre seems to offer some compensation. Still, after} Re8 13. O-O-O Kf8
$17 {[%cal Gf8g8] Black has nice chances of consolidating the material
advantage.}) 9... Nxe4 $1 {This leads by force to an unbalanced position.} 10.
Nxe4 (10. Bxe7 Nxc3 11. Qc4 $2 {now is bad due to} Nxa2+ $1) 10... Bxh4 11.
Nxe6 $1 {White needs to play concretely, otherwise Black is simply a pawn up.}
Bxe6 12. Nxd6+ Kf8 13. Nxf7 $1 Bg5+ $1 {An important intermediate to remember.}
(13... Bxf7 $2 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Qf3 $36 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf1c4] ;
Solodovnichenko, Y (2587)-Fier, A (2624) FRA-chT Top 12 2016 (3.4) 1/2-1/2
gives some initiative for White.}) 14. Kb1 (14. f4 $5 {is an attempt to
attract the bishop to a more exposed position.} Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 Kxf7 16. Rxd8
Rxd8 17. Qf3 {[%csl Rb7,Rf4] The point of White's idea. However, Black has the
nice reply} Kg8 $1 {avoiding both threats thanks to back rank motifs.}) 14...
Kxf7 15. Rxd8 Rxd8 $44 {Black has enough material for the queen. If we achieve
a nice coordination our pieces certainly will be stronger than White's queen.})
(7. Qd2 {is also a popular move (even more than 7.Qf3) but I don't think it
matches with the bishop on g5.} Be7 8. f4 $6 ({It's safer to play} 8. f3 {or})
(8. O-O-O b5 9. f3 {transposing to 7.f3.}) 8... b5 $1 $132 {[%csl Gd2,Gf3]
[%cal Gc8b7,Yb5b4] This is the drawback of developing the queen to d2: Black
can develop active play on the queenside more easily. Here Black already has a
good game and White needs to be careful to not end up in an inferior position.}
) (7. Qd3 {also has been tried. We can exploit this move in the same way as 7.
Qd2 with} b5 $1 8. O-O-O Nbd7 $1 {The correct move order.} (8... Bb7 $6 {allows
} 9. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 10. e5 $1 $36 {[%cal Gd3h3] when White suddenly gets a
dangerous initiative.}) 9. f4 $6 {This is connected with a thematic idea which
however doesn't work here.} (9. a3 {is safer, but after something like} Bb7 10.
Kb1 Be7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 11. f3 {Black has a normal game, while White's position
doesn't make sense at all for me.}) 9... b4 $1 {Disturbing White's
coordination.} 10. Nd5 $2 {White played this thematic sacrifice in 8 games,
but it is simply a mistake.} ({In case of} 10. Nce2 Nc5 11. Qf3 Bb7 12. Ng3 Be7
13. Bd3 O-O $17 {[%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4,Yb4b3] Black also has a very good position.}
) 10... exd5 11. exd5 Nc5 $1 {This basically refutes White's idea.} 12. Re1+
Kd7 13. Qc4 Bb7 $19 {Hagarova,Z (2321)-Womacka,M (2486) Pardubice KB op 2000  
(7) 0-1 Black had no problems to stop the attack and easily converted the
