Ra7 28. O-O $44 {White has enough compensation for the pawn, but not more.} ({
But not} 28. Bc5 $2 b6 29. Bxb6 Rb7 30. Ba5 Nc6 $19 {[%csl Ra5,Rc7] and White
loses a piece.})) 16... Bc5 17. Bg3 Qd5 $1 {It's important to provoke c4 by
White before exchanging on d4.} 18. c4 Bxd4 $1 19. Rxd4 Qa5+ 20. Rd2 O-O 21.
Bd6 {White makes the possible to keep posing practical problems for Black
aiming to exploit the better development. However, we have a nice idea to
relieve the pressure:} f5 $1 22. Bxf8 Nxf8 23. Nd6 Nbd7 $44 {[%cal Ga5c5,Gd7c5,
Ga8b8,Yb7b5,Gc8d7] The exchange sacrifice is the best practical solution for
Black. Now we have prevented the direct threats and can mobilize our pieces in
the next moves. A typical plan here is to exchange queens, as in that case
