Be6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Rad1 Rfd8 $15 {Brandenburg,D (2535)-Giri, A (2687)
NED-ch Boxtel 2011 (6) 0-1 The position should be equal with correct play but
in practice, I already like it more for Black, as White's structural
weaknesses tend to be more unpleasant to defend in the long run.}) 8... b5 $1 {
A nice point about this move order is that Black always gets active play on
the queenside.} 9. a3 (9. Bg2 {seems less effective as Black has already
expanded on the queenside. After} Bb7 10. O-O Be7 11. f4 Nc6 {I like Black's
position. We have a normal development and White can face problems with the
overextended kingside sometimes.}) 9... Bb7 10. h4 {Following the plan on the
kingside. Instead of developing the bishop on g2, White keeps it on f1 and
goes for an English Attack-like set-up.} Nc6 $1 {Black doesn't need to hurry
up to develop the f8-bishop, it's better to keep mobilizing our queenside.} 11.
Be3 ({In 3 games White started with} 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Be3 {but I think this
is helpful for Black, as the bishop seems better placed on c6 to support the
counterplay on the queenside.} Be7 13. Qd4 O-O 14. O-O-O Rb8 $1 {[%cal Ya6a5,
Yb5b4] Here we can see why the exchange on c6 is more useful for Black.} 15. h5
{White's attack looks faster, but Black has a nice defensive idea:} Nc5 $1 ({
But not} 15... Bxg5 $2 16. Rg1 Bxe3+ 17. Qxe3 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge3g3,Ge3h6]
and White has strong compensation for the pawn.}) 16. f3 (16. h6 $2 {was
played in one game, but after} e5 $1 17. Qd2 g6 {[%cal Gc5e6] Black's kingside
is safe. After} 18. f3 a5 $5 $36 {Barbosa,E  (2438)-Mareco, S (2581) American
Continental 11th 2015 (6) 0-1 the initiative is already with Black.}) 16... a5
$5 {Black should keep the focus on the queenside.} 17. b4 $8 {White is
basically forced to play this move in order to slow down Black's attack on the
queenside, but after} axb4 18. axb4 e5 $1 19. Qd2 Ne6 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gb8a8,
Yd6d5] The position is very tense. In practice I think White has the biggest
dangers, as Black often threatens a decisive invasion on the queenside. For
example:} 20. Rg1 $2 {too slow.} (20. g6 $5 {is probably better, trying to get
counterchances on the kingside.}) 20... Ra8 21. Kb2 Qc7 22. g6 {Now Black has
the strong reply} d5 $3 {with a crushing attack:} 23. Nxd5 Bxd5 24. exd5 Bxb4
$3 25. Qxb4 Ra2+ $1 26. Kxa2 Qxc2+ $19 {[%cal Gf8a8] and mate. A beautiful
illustration of Black's tactical possibilities.}) 11... Be7 12. Qd2 O-O 13.
O-O-O Nc5 {With the bishop on f1 the threat of Nc4 is harmless, so we should
press in the centre.} 14. f3 (14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. f3 {is an imprecise move order
in view of} Qb8 $1 $40 {[%cal Gf8c8,Ya6a5,Yb5b4] ;Hansen, M (2452)-Sethuraman,
S (2647) Hastings Masters op 92nd 2016 (6) 0-1 when Black achieves a very
dangerous set-up to develop the attack on the queenside.}) 14... Rb8 $1 {
[%cal Gb8b1,Ya6a5,Yb5b4] A nice and important move to remember, not just here
but also in similar positions. In Sicilian positions the rook is usually well
placed on c8, but here the main source of counterplay for Black is the advance
of the queenside pawns, so the rook should go to b8 in order to support this
plan always as possible.} 15. Kb1 {This might look scary with the rook on b8,
but White has enough resources to keep the king safe.} ({It's also possible to
consider} 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. b4 $5 {trying to slow down Black's counterplay.
However, after} Nd7 17. h5 a5 $13 {[%cal Gb8a8] ;Harika,D (2521)-Yilmaz,M 
(2614) Reykjavik op 2017 (8) 1/2-1/2 the position is complex and double-edged,
with similar ideas as those seen in the notes of 11.Nxc6.}) ({In case of} 15.
Rg1 {Black has} b4 $5 {A nice detail to remember is that after} 16. Nxc6 Bxc6
17. axb4 {Black plays} Qb6 $1 ({But not} 17... Rxb4 $2 18. Nd5 $1 {with
advantage for White.}) 18. Na2 $2 a5 $1 $40 {with a strong attack.}) 15... Qc7
{A necessary measure to prepare b4.} (15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bc6 {has the same
idea seen in some previous lines. The difference is that Black is a tempo down
now, and White has the strong reply} 17. Qh2 $1 $36 {[%cal Yh4h5,Yg5g6,Gd1d8]
with many annoying threats.}) ({The immediate} 15... b4 $2 {is bad due to} 16.
Nxc6 Bxc6 17. axb4 Rxb4 18. Nd5 $1 $16) 16. h5 ({As usual, in case of} 16. Nxc6
Bxc6 17. b4 $5 Nd7 $13 {[%cal Ya6a5,Gd7e5,Ge5c4] the position is extremely
tense.}) 16... b4 $1 {Now the advance works nicely.} 17. axb4 ({The difference
is that if} 17. Nxc6 Bxc6 18. axb4 Rxb4 19. Nd5 {Black has} Rxb2+ $1 20. Kxb2
Rb8+ {[%csl Gb8][%cal Gf8b8] bringing another rook to the queenside. After} 21.
Ka1 exd5 $40 {[%csl Ra1] Although the engine evaluates as equal, White's
position looks very dangerous for me.}) 17... Nxb4 18. g6 $1 {White finally
manages to break through on the kingside and the position becomes very complex.
} (18. Nde2 $2 {Popov, I (2604)-Radovanovic, M (2496) SRB-chT Subotica 2019 (8.
3) 1/2-1/2 was played in one game, but it is too passive. Black missed the
strong move} Bc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a4] when White lacks a good way of facing the
threat of Ba4. For example:} 19. g6 Ba4 20. Rc1 Bxc2+ $1 21. Rxc2 Nb3 $19 {
[%cal Gc7a5,Ga5a1] with a quick mate.}) 18... Bf6 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Another key
move to remember: the bishop assumes both attacking and defensive tasks in the
long diagonal.} 19. Bh3 $5 {White keeps increasing the tension on the kingside.
Here Black should be careful and play} Bc8 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gb8b1] an
important prophylactic move, cleaning the b-file and overprotecting e6.} (19...
Qa5 $2 {seems more natural, but Black had serious problems after} 20. Nb3 $1
Nxb3 21. cxb3 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge3d4] ;Kulaots,K (2542)-Yilmaz,M (2633)
Olympiad-43 Batumi 2018 (9.1) 1-0 The bad news for Black is that} Bxc3 {
is simply answered by} 22. bxc3 $18 {[%cal Gd2a2]}) 20. Nde2 {[%cal Ge3d4]
Exchanging the dark-squared bishops seems a logical way of improving White's
position. However, Black can play in a concrete way with} (20. h6 $2 {is
harmless due to} fxg6 21. hxg7 Rf7 $1 $19 {[%csl Ge6] Here we can see the
importance of reinforcing the e6-pawn.}) 20... Na2 $5 {forcing a repetition.} (
20... Qb7 $5 {is an option to keep the tension.}) 21. Kxa2 (21. Bd4 {now looks
risky only for White:} Bxd4 22. Qxd4 (22. Nxd4 $2 {allows the unexpected blow}
